===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|smilen||to smile}}, of {{etyl|gmq|en}} origin, from {{etyl|da|-}} {{m|da|smile||to smile}}, from {{etyl|non|en}} {{m|non|*smíla||to smile}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*smīlijaną}}, {{m|gem-pro|*smirōną||to smile}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*(s)meyh₂-||to laugh, be glad, wonder}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sv|-}} {{m|sv|smila||to smile}}, Low German {{m|nds|smielen||to smile}}, Saterland Frisian {{m|stq|smielje||to smile}}, Dutch {{m|nl|smuilen||to smile}}, {{etyl|gmh|-}} {{m|gmh|smielen||to smile}}, {{etyl|goh|-}} {{m|goh|smierōn||to smile}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{m|ang|smerian||to laugh at}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{m|ang|smercian}}, {{m|ang|smearcian||to smile}}, {{etyl|la|-}} {{m|la|miror||to wonder at}}. More at {{l|en|smirk}}.

a smile is when you curve the sides of your lips, into a smile. when you smile, your usually amused, happy, proud, relieved, or joyful.

===Verb===
{{en-verb|smil}}

# {{label|en|ambitransitive}} To have (a [[smile]]) on one's face.
#: {{ux|en|When you '''smile''', the whole world '''smiles''' with you.&nbsp;&nbsp; I don't know what he's '''smiling''' about.&nbsp;&nbsp; She '''smiles''' a beautiful smile.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1918|author={{w|W. B. Maxwell}}|chapter=7
|title=[http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1097634W The Mirror and the Lamp]
|passage=“[…] This is Mr. Churchill, who, as you are aware, is good enough to come to us for his diaconate, and, as we hope, for much longer; and being a gentleman of independent means, he declines to take any payment.” Saying this Walden rubbed his hands together and '''smiled''' contentedly.}}
# {{label|en|transitive}} To express by smiling.
#* {{quote-book|year=1898|author={{w|Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill}}
|title={{w|The Celebrity}}|chapter=2
|passage=I had occasion […] to make a somewhat long business trip to Chicago, and on my return […] I found Farrar awaiting me in the railway station. He '''smiled''' his wonted fraction by way of greeting, […], and finally leading me to his buggy, turned and drove out of town. I was completely mystified at such an unusual proceeding.}}
#: {{ux|en|to '''smile''' consent, or a welcome}}
# {{label|en|intransitive}} To express amusement, pleasure, or love and kindness. <!--without the mouth-->
#* Byron
#*: When last I saw thy young blue eyes, they '''smiled'''.
# {{label|en|intransitive}} To look cheerful and joyous; to have an appearance suited to excite joy.
#: ''The sun '''smiled''' down from a clear summer sky.''
#* Alexander Pope
#*: The desert '''smiled''', / And paradise was opened in the wild.
# {{label|en|intransitive}} To be propitious or favourable; to countenance.
#: ''The gods '''smiled''' on his labours.''

